analysis:
Across the better-scoring heuristics a clear, repeatable pipeline emerges: (1) deterministic Pareto prefilter, (2) cheap per-point proxies (axis-aligned box volume and small-weight scalarizations) to rank and form an adaptive shortlist, (3) a greedy/CELF-style insertion using cached singleton HVs (plus selective pairwise caches), and (4) a bounded 1-for-1 local-swap cleanup. The strongest variants emphasize (a) small but k-proportional shortlists to limit costly hv.compute calls, (b) CELF lazy updates to avoid recomputing stale gains, (c) deterministic tie-breakers and RNG seeds, and (d) modest pairwise caching when shortlist ≤ ~40 to accelerate marginal checks.

Weak/slow designs (e.g., GSI_LS) perform many full HV recomputations inside nested loops, use randomized initial states without deterministic tie-breaks, or omit CELF-style laziness—leading to excessive hv calls and nondeterministic behavior. Approaches that replace exact HVs with massive weight-vector approximations trade HV-call cost for heavy memory/time in the approximation stage and can misrank borderline candidates.

Common avoidable overheads spotted:
- repeated full-array assembly and hv.compute calls inside tight loops (recompute entire selected-set HV instead of using cached/incremental deltas);
- Python-level "in" membership checks on lists/sets in hot loops rather than boolean masks/arrays;
- rebuilding vstack arrays every candidate test instead of reusing buffers or incremental updates;
- unbounded shortlist sizes or swap budgets that scale poorly.

Practical tradeoffs visible in the set: smaller shortlists + CELF + cached singletons deliver large reductions in HV calls and predictable runtime, while careful pairwise caching and limited swap budgets yield extra HV gains with bounded cost. Heuristics that use many weight vectors can approximate HVC well but must be balanced against the O(num_weights * N * D) cost; they can be effective as a prefilter if kept moderate.
